</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Chairman / Interim Chief Executive Officer </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Effective as of October&nbsp;26, 2011, we entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Michael J. Ahearn, our chairman, to serve as
our chairman and chief executive officer. With the appointment of Mr.&nbsp;Hughes as our chief executive officer effective May&nbsp;3, 2012, Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn became our executive chairman. He resigned as an employee of the Company on July&nbsp;30,
2012, and effective July&nbsp;31, 2012, became our non-executive chairman. His 2012 non-associate director compensation was pro-rated accordingly. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Cash Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The annual cash compensation for our non-associate
directors is $75,000 (payable quarterly in four equal installments) plus an additional $75,000 (payable quarterly in four equal installments) for the non-executive chairman of the board, an additional $35,000 annual cash retainer (payable quarterly
in four equal installments) for the chairman of our audit committee and an additional $10,000 annual cash retainer (payable quarterly in four equal installments) for the other four committee chairs. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Equity Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
annual equity compensation for our non-associate directors is a $100,000 stock grant, (granted quarterly in four equal installments), plus an additional annual $100,000 (granted quarterly in four equal installments) for the
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">13 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
non-executive chairman of the board. With respect to such quarterly stock grants, our practice is to issue the stock to our non-associate directors at the end of the quarter. Our practice is not
to time the date of these awards, and we do not take into account any internal &#147;black outs,&#148; during which associates and directors are prohibited by our Insider Trading Policy from trading in our securities, without regard to whether they
are in possession of undisclosed material facts or whether any undisclosed material facts could be perceived as potentially positive or negative. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Other </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We reimburse all non-associate directors for reasonable and
necessary expenses they incur in performing their duties as non-associate directors of the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2012, Compensation
Strategies, Inc., our independent compensation consultant, performed a market study for our non-associate director compensation. Based on the results of the study, the board of directors approved revised director compensation on November&nbsp;28,
2012. Effective January&nbsp;1, 2013, non-associate director compensation was revised to $100,000 annual cash compensation and $125,000 annual equity compensation, in each case, payable on the same terms as described above. The annual cash and
equity compensation for the non-executive chairman of the board and the additional annual cash compensation for each of our committee chairmen did not change. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT

an investment adviser in accordance with Section&nbsp;240.13d-1(b)(1)(ii)(E), and Morgan Stanley is a parent holding company or control person in accordance with Rule 13d-1(b)(1)(ii)(G). </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

exceeded or will exceed $120,000 and in which any current director, executive officer, holder of more than five percent of our capital stock, or any member of the immediate family of any of the foregoing, had or will have a material interest, other
than in connection with the transactions described below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Related Party Debt </B></FONT></P>

ended December&nbsp;31, 2012. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Registration Rights </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT

Holdings, LLC and Estate of John T. Walton are now held by JCL FSLR Holdings, LLC. The registration rights agreement provides for piggyback registration rights if we register equity securities under the Securities Act of 1933, as

obtained from unaffiliated parties. If a member of the audit committee has an interest in the proposed transaction, our corporate governance guidelines require the formation of a committee consisting entirely of independent directors without an
interest in the proposed transaction to review and, if appropriate, approve such transaction. </FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The audit committee has policies and procedures that require the pre-approval by the audit committee of all fees paid to, and all services
performed by, the Company&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, subject to <I>de minimis</I> exceptions for non-audit services set forth in the applicable rules of the Commission. Each year, the audit committee pre-approves the
proposed services, including the nature, type and scope of services to be performed by the independent registered public accounting firm during the fiscal year and the related fees. Audit committee pre-approval is also required for those engagements
that may arise during the course of the year that are outside the scope of the initial services and fees pre-approved by the audit committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The services related to Audit-Related Fees, Tax Fees and All Other Fees presented in the above table were approved by the audit committee pursuant to pre-approval provisions set forth in the applicable
rules of the Commission without resort to a waiver of such pre-approval provisions. </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc480244_7"></A>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Executive Summary </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">First
Solar is a leading global provider of comprehensive photovoltaic (&#147;PV&#148;) solar systems that use our advanced thin-film modules. The Company&#146;s integrated power plant solutions deliver an economically attractive alternative to
today&#146;s fossil-fuel electricity generation. In response to a rapidly changing and highly-competitive solar industry, we implemented a long-term strategic plan (&#147;Long Term Strategic Plan&#148;), which focuses our attention on utility-scale
solar solutions that shifts emphasis away from subsidized markets and towards more sustainable ones. Our Long Term Strategic Plan, which we began to execute against in late 2011, impacted many of our compensation decisions for 2012. It did not,
however, change the core philosophy underlying our compensation decisions: we pay executives for performance and seek to align the interests of our executives with our stockholders. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Although 2012 was a challenging and highly competitive year in the industry, we have made significant progress toward our goal of
refocusing our business development efforts into sustainable markets. To that end, we now have teams in China, India, Australia, South Africa, Chile and certain parts of the Middle East and are beginning to see results as we successfully execute on
our Long Term Strategic Plan. We also made significant changes in our leadership structure and worked diligently on a number of key compensation decisions, which are highlighted below: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Changes in Leadership Structure.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>In 2012, we appointed a new chief executive officer, Mr.&nbsp;James&nbsp;A. Hughes, as
well as a new chief operating officer, Mr.&nbsp;Georges Antoun. Prior to joining the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Hughes most recently served as the chief executive officer of a company that owned and operated power distribution, power generation (both thermal
and renewable), natural gas transportation and natural gas distribution businesses in emerging markets worldwide. Mr.&nbsp;Antoun has over 20 years of operational and technical experience at various companies, including leadership positions at
several global technology companies. These executives play a key role in the implementation of our Long Term Strategic Plan, and have seamlessly transitioned into their new roles working closely with other members of our senior leadership team,
whose roles have also evolved in connection with our Long Term Strategic Plan. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>KSTEPP Equity Program</I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;One of the most significant changes we made to executive compensation was the implementation in
May 2012 of the Key Senior Talent Equity Performance Program, or &#147;KSTEPP&#148;, a very long-term performance equity program that applies to our key senior executives. The KSTEPP rewards achievement of rigorous performance objectives aligned to
the success of our Long Term Strategic Plan, which if achieved should create significant value for our stockholders. The performance objectives for the rolling annual measurement periods include KSTEPP adjusted operating income (defined below),
sales (in gigawatts DC) in sustainable markets and cash adjusted return on invested capital (defined below). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Elimination of New Tax Gross-ups.</I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Consistent with the decision we made in 2011 to cease granting 280G tax gross-ups in
new executive agreements, we did not include tax gross-up provisions in the employment agreements for Messrs. Hughes and Antoun. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Clawback Policy</I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company has included clawback provisions with respect to compensation awards in 2012 that will allow
us to recoup, to the extent required by applicable law, incentive payments made to our named executive officers if we later determine that the basis on which such compensation was earned was erroneous. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Hedging Policy</I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company&#146;s hedging policy prohibits our directors and associates, including all named executive
officers, from (i)&nbsp;engaging in any short sales with respect to any Company securities, (ii)&nbsp;buying or selling puts, calls or derivatives on any Company securities and (iii)&nbsp;purchasing any Company securities on margin.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Share Ownership Guidelines</I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company remains committed to reviewing and tracking the implementation of the share
ownership guidelines we adopted in February 2010. We amended these guidelines in 2012 to increase the chief executive officer&#146;s required holdings from five times to six times base pay. In addition, on the recommendation of our independent
compensation consultant and to conform to market practice, we amended the guidelines to allow executives and directors five, rather than three, years to obtain the required ownership levels. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">19 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Overview </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The individuals in the Summary Compensation Table below are referred to in this Compensation Discussion and Analysis as the &#147;named executive officers.&#148; Our named executive officers for 2012
were: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Ms.&nbsp;Mary Beth Gustafsson, executive vice president, general counsel and corporate secretary. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The last two years have seen turmoil and dramatic change in the solar power generation industry. This challenging environment has been
characterized by intense pricing competition, declining operating incomes, manufacturing slow-downs or shut-downs, and even the bankruptcy of some competitors. The Company has responded with a change in senior leadership and the development of a new
multi-year strategic plan, which we refer to as our Long Term Strategic Plan. Our Long Term Strategic Plan was implemented at the end of 2011 and consists primarily of (i)&nbsp;a strategic focus on utility-scale solar solutions in emerging regions
and markets, thereby shifting emphasis away from subsidized markets towards more financially sustainable markets, and (ii)&nbsp;an organizational restructuring that, among other things, focused our efforts on providing a range of utility-scale solar
solutions through global business development initiatives. The ultimate goals of our Long Term Strategic Plan are to increase business growth, improve profitability and enhance liquidity. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Long Term Strategic Plan represents a comprehensive strategy for the Company, and, in order to ensure leadership alignment with that
strategy, required us to reevaluate our approach to compensation to ensure that it reflected the elements needed to effectively compensate and retain the senior leadership team during this difficult transition period. We ultimately concluded that
our existing compensation philosophy was generally well-suited to the aims of our Long Term Strategic Plan, but recognized that some changes were necessary in light of the uncertainty and challenges endemic to this transition. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Context and Overview </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>- Calibrating Performance Metrics and Compensation Components in Light of our Long Term Strategic Plan.</I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The compensation committee has adopted changes that are consistent
with the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy in order to best align our compensation practices with our Long Term Strategic Plan, including selecting a revised peer group that better reflects the evolving profile of the Company and solar power
industry, adopting a new very long-term equity program (the KSTEPP, described below), and adjusting base salaries and target bonuses based, in part, on prospective considerations relating to our Long Term Strategic Plan. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-<I> Extraordinary Measures to Stabilize and Retain our Associate Base.</I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The challenges of 2011 and 2012 across
the industry were also felt within the Company, evidenced by unusually high levels of executive attrition, instability in the Company&#146;s stock price and expectations of low realized compensation. In order to address anxiety among our associates
and to renew dedication and focus, the compensation committee determined to offer retention awards to certain associates. For our named executive officers, the retention awards are intended to work in tandem with the KSTEPP long-term equity awards
to encourage the engagement and long-term investment of our executives in the success of our Long Term Strategic Plan. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>- We
have Considered our Stockholder&#146;s Feedback Regarding our Compensation Practices.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>At the 2011 annual meeting, the stockholder advisory vote on the Company&#146;s executive compensation (&#147;say on pay&#148;) was
approved by 89.3% of our stockholders voting, and a triennial cycle for the next executive compensation advisory vote was selected by 69.5% of the stockholders voting on the timing of such votes (&#147;say when on pay&#148;). The compensation
committee, taking these results into account, continued with its executive compensation philosophy and adopted a triennial cycle for the say on pay advisory votes. Accordingly, the Company did not conduct a say on
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">20 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
pay advisory vote at its 2012 annual meeting and is not conducting a say on pay advisory vote at the 2013 annual meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>First Solar Compensation Philosophy </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">First Solar&#146;s compensation
philosophy rests on foundational principles that inform the way we design our compensation programs and pay our named executive officers. This philosophy can be understood in the following ways: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>- First Solar Pay is Simple and is Designed to Align the Interests of Executive Management and
Stockholders.</I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company&#146;s approach to compensation is straightforward, and this is reflected in the components of our executive&#146;s aggregate annual pay. The three primary components of First Solar executive
compensation are: (1)&nbsp;base salary, (2)&nbsp;cash incentive compensation (short-term incentive) and (3)&nbsp;equity compensation (long-term incentive). Our named executive officers have the largest percentage of total compensation at risk (i.e.,
the portion of compensation that is not payable to such executives unless certain performance targets are achieved) with a heavy weighting towards equity compensation to align their interests with stockholders. There are no supplemental executive
retirement programs or other deferred compensation arrangements and generally no perquisites that are available solely for the named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-<I> Our Compensation Levels are Consistent with Market Levels, and We Apply Discretion to Conform to, or Reward, Actual Performance.</I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that our named executive
officers should be compensated at a level that ensures their continued dedication to the Company and creates potential rewards for extraordinary results when advancing the goals and strategy of the Company, particularly with respect to the
implementation of our Long Term Strategic Plan. The Company works with an independent compensation consultant, Compensation Strategies, Inc., who annually compiles and analyzes market data to determine the pay practices of our peer group, which we
use in determining the level of our named executive officers&#146; pay (generally targeted at the 50th percentile, with deviations possible when warranted by role, skill set, performance or other extraordinary considerations). See &#147;Compensation
Committee Practices &#150; Total Compensation Review&#148;. Similarly, our choice of metrics (both financial and operating) related to our annual incentive plan and KSTEPP, and the compensation committee&#146;s discretion to reduce awards granted
under the annual incentive plan, are meant to ensure that our named executive officers are not rewarded unless performance goals are achieved and that operational metrics are not achieved at the expense of financial performance. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Executive Compensation Policies </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The compensation committee has responsibility for establishing and overseeing our compensation program as it applies to our named executive officers. The compensation committee bases its executive
compensation programs on the policies set forth below, which have generally remained constant from prior years: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="39%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="59%"></TD></TR>


<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Pay To Market</I></B></FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Compensation should be based on the level of job responsibility, individual performance and Company performance. Compensation should also reflect the value of the job in the
marketplace. To attract and retain a highly skilled work force, we must provide pay that remains competitive with the pay of other employers who compete with us for talent.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD HEIGHT="8"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>More Responsibility, More Pay at Risk; We Pay for Performance</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As associates progress to higher levels in the organization, an increasing proportion of their pay should be linked to Company performance and stockholder returns because they
are better able, relative to other associates, to affect the Company&#146;s results.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD HEIGHT="8"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Metrics Should Motivate Associates to Achieve the Mission</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To be effective, performance-based compensation programs should enable associates to easily understand how their efforts can affect their pay, both through individual performance
and through contributing to the Company&#146;s achievement of its strategic and operational goals.</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">21 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Evaluating the Market.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>Although our determination of the
amount and mix of compensation elements for our named executive officers is generally not influenced by short-term market shifts, when extraordinary business changes occur, such as occurred for the Company in 2011 and 2012, we believe that our
compensation practices should include the requisite flexibility to respond to those changes while remaining consistent with our compensation philosophy. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">When setting compensation, we review compensation paid by other companies of comparable size in the same or similar industries and where our compensation falls within our peer group. Depending on the
role, the experience an individual brings to the role, and individual performance, we broadly aim to set our executive base salary and incentive targets at the 50th percentile of our peer group, although depending on the role, the experience an
individual brings to the role and individual performance, we may set executive base salaries and/or incentives closer to the 75th percentile. In other words, our objective is to generally pay median compensation while providing an opportunity to
increase compensation further through successful performance in our incentive compensation programs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We do not exclusively
rely on market data to determine executive compensation. Instead, we incorporate flexibility into our compensation program and in our assessment process to respond to and adjust for the dynamic business environment in which we operate. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Equity Policies.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>To better align the interests of executives with those of our stockholders, we previously
adopted share ownership guidelines that cover our officers, including the named executive officers, and certain other members of senior management, which we amended during 2012 to, among other changes, increase the chief executive officer&#146;s
required holdings from five times to six times base pay. We also prohibit our associates from engaging in hedging transactions with respect to our shares.<I> </I> </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">22 </FONT></P>

incentive compensation (i.e., an annual bonus) and long-term equity-based compensation, which components are described in the chart below, including how each component fits into our overall executive compensation package (i.e., the particular
objectives and the specific elements that our compensation programs are designed to address). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#252;</FONT></FONT> <P STYLE="font-size:14px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px">&nbsp;</P></TD>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each of our named executive officers (other than Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn) is party to an employment agreement and
change in control agreement that protect him or her in the event of certain employment terminations, as well as confidentiality and non-competition agreements. Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn, who served as our interim chief executive officer through May&nbsp;3,
2012 and our executive chairman through July&nbsp;30, 2012, was party to employment and confidentiality agreements only. The employment and change in control agreements provide severance, in exchange for a release of claims, and equity vesting
acceleration as described in more detail in &#147;Employment Agreements and Related Arrangements&#148; and &#147;Change in Control Severance Agreements.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Generally, the types of compensation and benefits provided to the named executive officers are similar to those provided to other members of our senior leadership team. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">23 </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Compensation Committee Practices </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Review of Peer Company Data </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On at least a bi-annual basis, but typically annually, the compensation committee evaluates the compensation payable to our named executive officers against data regarding the pay practices of companies
in our peer group, looking at individual components of pay, including total amount paid or payable. In addition, the compensation committee annually reviews any payments to our named executive officers that would be required under various severance
scenarios. When conducting this review, the compensation committee also considers information and recommendations from management regarding past, present and future compensation of our named executive officers under various payment scenarios.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As part of its annual review and as a general update, the compensation committee determined in July 2011 to reevaluate its
peer group. Based in part on feedback from its independent compensation consultant, Compensation Strategies, Inc., and on estimates of the Company&#146;s annual performance for 2011, the Company recast its peer group to add companies from whom it
hired key talent or that related to the Company&#146;s new areas of focus (including construction and power solutions) and to remove companies that were recently acquired or who were no longer financially comparable to the Company. By the end of
2011, mindful of the difficulties that led to our Long Term Strategic Plan and the rapidly changing profile of the solar power industry, the compensation committee further refined the peer group to better reflect the Company&#146;s changed business
environment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2012, the compensation committee again retained Compensation Strategies, Inc. as a consultant to provide data
and analysis regarding the selection of companies in our peer group, the pay practices of such companies and results of a comparison of each of the components of the compensation of our named executive officers against the compensation paid to
executives in similarly-situated positions at our peer group companies. The consultant&#146;s benchmarking services were limited to comparing each element of compensation for a particular position against similar elements in the peer group. For
compensation decisions made in the first two quarters of 2012, the compensation committee relied on data from the interim peer group formed in July 2011, upon assurances from the consultant that the data and percentile references for the interim
peer group were substantially similar to those applicable to the current peer group. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The consultant&#146;s 2012 report
supported the determination that the compensation paid to the Company&#146;s named executive officers was consistent with the Company&#146;s stated compensation objectives regarding our target pay as compared to our peer group, and was thus
reasonable in the aggregate as compared to the peer group below. See &#147;Executive Compensation Policies &#151; Evaluating the Market.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The aggregate fees paid to Compensation Strategies, Inc. for 2012 services were $316,465. The fees were incurred solely for services relating to executive and board compensation. During 2012, the
compensation committee conducted an independence analysis of the relationship of Compensation Strategies, Inc. to the Company, including a review of potential conflicts of interest, and concluded that Compensation Strategies, Inc. is independent.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s 2012 peer group is comprised of the following companies, including U.S.-based companies in the solar
sector, and companies in the hi-tech and high precision manufacturing, non-high tech manufacturing, renewable energy and construction and engineering sectors, which had annual revenues ranging from $956 million to $23.4 billion and market
capitalization ranging from $536 million to $34.9 billion:</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">24 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Individual Compensation Review </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The individual performance of our named executive officers has been, and continues to be, a major factor in the compensation
committee&#146;s decision regarding the executive&#146;s level of compensation. Generally, absent unusual circumstances, our process for review of individual compensation of our named executive officers is as follows. After the completion of each
year, our independent directors (meeting in executive session under the direction of the chair of the compensation committee) review the performance of our chief executive officer for the prior year, evaluating his achievement against individual and
Company objectives (which objectives were agreed upon between him and the compensation committee early in the prior year), his contributions to the Company&#146;s performance and other leadership accomplishments. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our chief executive officer provides the compensation committee with an assessment of prior year performance of, and a recommendation for
compensation changes with respect to, our other named executive officers, evaluating each executive based on achievement of preset objectives by the executive and his or her organization, his or her contribution to the Company&#146;s performance and
other leadership accomplishments. Based on these considerations, and following an exercise of its independent judgment on the board&#146;s interactions with the named executive officers, the compensation committee (i)&nbsp;sets base salary, target
bonus percentages and the basis for each executive&#146;s participation in the long-term equity-based incentive program for the current year and (ii)&nbsp;determines whether to award cash-incentive compensation for the prior year. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with the implementation of our Long Term Strategic Plan, review of, and decisions regarding compensation relating to, our
named executive officers in 2012 were deferred until the second quarter of the year. Unlike in prior years, the compensation committee&#146;s decision regarding pay increases and awards in 2012 was influenced in part by prospective considerations
regarding the measures that would most effectively ensure the uninterrupted focus of our named executive officers during this key transitional time. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Compensation Risk Analysis </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In the context of the total compensation
review and the adoption of the Company&#146;s 2012 incentive programs, the compensation committee considered whether the Company&#146;s compensation structure and programs encourage excessive or inappropriate risk taking. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>2012 Compensation Decisions </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following is a discussion of the considerations in establishing each of the compensation components for named executive officers in 2012. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Base Salary </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Base salary is the fixed element of our named executive officers&#146; annual cash compensation. The value of base salary for each named executive officer reflects the requirements of such
executive&#146;s employment agreement, and his or her individual performance and skill set, including the market value of that skill set. The Company seeks to establish or maintain base salary levels for our executives between the 50th and 75th
percentile (with the expectation that generally any compensation paid at a level above the 50th percentile is warranted only due to extraordinary performance, critical skill sets or similar considerations). Based on our assessment of individual
performance and individual skill sets, the aggregate base salary and target bonus percentage for most of our named executive officers is positioned between the 50th and 75th percentile. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The compensation committee evaluates market data and individual performance of executives during our regular annual salary review process,
which we refer to as our &#147;annual pay cycle.&#148; At the beginning of 2012, the base salaries of our named executive officers (other than Messrs.&nbsp;Hughes and Antoun, who are discussed below) were as follows: Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn ($500,000);
Mr.&nbsp;Widmar ($435,000); Mr.&nbsp;Brown ($450,000); and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson ($400,000). During the 2012 pay cycle, the compensation committee established the base salaries of the named executive officers (other than for Messrs. Hughes and Antoun)
as follows, which includes, for Mr.&nbsp;Widmar, a marked increase in base salary that the compensation committee felt was appropriate in recognition of his additional </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">25 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
responsibilities related to his support of our chief executive officer, as well as the assumption of the chief accounting officer responsibilities: Mr.&nbsp;Widmar ($550,000); Mr.&nbsp;Brown
($455,000); and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson ($442,000). Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn&#146;s base salary was unchanged. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Mid-Year Changes and
Related Salary Adjustments.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>The Company hired Mr.&nbsp;Hughes as chief commercial officer, effective March&nbsp;19, 2012, at a base salary of $550,000, and on May&nbsp;3, 2012, the Company appointed Mr.&nbsp;Hughes as
chief executive officer, effective immediately, pursuant to which his base salary rose from $550,000 to $750,000. The Company hired Mr.&nbsp;Antoun as chief operating officer, effective July&nbsp;1, 2012, at a base salary of $550,000. On
July&nbsp;30, 2012, Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn resigned as an employee of the Company, and effective July&nbsp;31, 2012, became the non-executive chairman of the Company&#146;s board of directors with annual cash compensation of $150,000. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Cash Incentive Compensation </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our cash incentive compensation consists primarily of our annual bonus program designed under our 2010 Omnibus Incentive Compensation Plan (the &#147;2010 Omnibus Plan&#148;) and cash sign-on bonuses that
we use to incentivize individuals to join our Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Annual Bonus Program.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>We use our annual
bonus program to reward achievement of specified strategic and operational objectives and focus on those objectives to help us achieve our mission of enabling a world powered by clean, affordable solar electricity. On February&nbsp;21, 2012, the
compensation committee adopted a 2012 bonus program for executives, including our named executive officers, with a single threshold operating metric as well as various performance metrics, each of which is assigned one of five weightings based on
the executive&#146;s function in the Company, to strengthen the connection between executive performance and incentive pay, which is one of our core executive compensation policies. Upon achievement of the threshold operating metric, the maximum
bonus pool will be funded, but the amount of each participant&#146;s actual bonus will be determined based on the achievement of various performance metrics, which may result in aggregate bonus payments less than the maximum bonus pool. Furthermore,
the compensation committee retains discretion to reduce any award achieved under the program to the extent appropriate. All bonus payments will be subject to clawback to the extent required by applicable law. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>- Bonus Program Targets, Objective and Calculation.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>The 2012 annual bonus program as applicable to our named
executive officers, had a $225 million adjusted operating income</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">1</SUP></FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> minimum threshold level and a matrix of the following five performance metrics, which were established based on the goals set forth in our confidential annual operating plan for 2012: (i)&nbsp;operating
cash flow, (ii)&nbsp;cost per watt (&#147;CPW&#148;), (iii)&nbsp;stabilized efficiency, (iv)&nbsp;megawatts (&#147;MW&#148;) shipped and (v)&nbsp;contribution margin. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each metric, other than adjusted operating income, was assigned a percentage weighting based on the importance of the factor to the overall performance of the Company. To better link the compensation
rewards with efforts, metric weightings were further differentiated based on the business/functional group to which the award recipient belongs. The weightings for Messrs. Hughes, Widmar and Antoun and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson, who are assigned to the
functions group, were as follows: (i)&nbsp;operating cash flow, 25%; (ii)&nbsp;CPW, 25%; (iii)&nbsp;stabilized efficiency, 20%; (iv)&nbsp;MW shipped, 15%; and (v)&nbsp;contribution margin, 15%. For Mr.&nbsp;Brown, each of the five metrics was
weighted equally, at 20%. The difference between the weightings for Mr.&nbsp;Brown relative to the other named executive officers is due to the fact that his primary function is related to sales. Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn did not participate in the annual
bonus program. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The levels of payout for each performance goal are expressed as a multiplier, ranging from a threshold of 0.5
in cases of weaker performance to 2.0 in cases of stronger performance. A 0.5 multiplier was assigned to performance at a level that, while not certain at the time targets were set, we considered likely that such performance would be achieved by the
end of the year. A 1.0 multiplier was assigned to performance at a level that, while not certain at the time targets were set, aligned with the goals in our annual operating plan, and thus was a level that we expected we could achieve by the end of
the year. A 2.0 multiplier was assigned to a performance </FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000;width:13%">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">1</SUP>&nbsp;</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;adjusted operating income&#148; means the Company&#146;s operating income (as defined by GAAP) with adjustments for (i)&nbsp;stock-based compensation expense,
(ii)&nbsp;restructuring expense, (iii)&nbsp;costs in excess of normal warranty and (iv)&nbsp;foreign currency (gain)/ loss. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
level that was substantially more uncertain (i.e., that we expected we would have approximately a 50% chance of achieving by year end). If the minimum threshold level of performance was not
achieved, the multiplier for the bonus was zero. The maximum bonus percentage payable under the 2012 annual bonus plan was 200% of target. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Based on an assessment of the 2012 Company results against the criteria described above, the bonus payout for Messrs. Hughes, Widmar and Antoun and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson was approximately 109%. Since
Mr.&nbsp;Hughes and Mr.&nbsp;Antoun did not complete a full year of service in 2012, their bonus payouts were prorated based on their period of service during 2012. Mr.&nbsp;Brown&#146;s bonus payout was 99%, reflecting the heavier weighting of the
sales-related metrics. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>- Target Bonus Percentage.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>Target bonus percentages were established
based on job responsibilities, internal equity and peer group data. Our objective is to generally set bonus targets at approximately the 50th percentile, with the ability to pay such bonuses above the 50th percentile when performance goals are
exceeded. Based on our assessment of the individual performance and skill sets, the aggregate base salary and target bonus percentage of our named executive officers are between the 50th and 75th percentile. Our practice puts us within the middle
range of peer group companies. Consistent with our executive compensation policy, our named executive officers had a greater proportion of their total cash compensation tied to Company performance through the cash incentive compensation program.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The target bonus percentage is evaluated during our annual pay cycle on the same basis as annual base salary (as discussed
above in &#147;2012 Compensation Decisions &#151; Base Salary&#148;). At the beginning of 2012, the target bonus percentages of our named executive officers (other than Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn, who did not participate in the program, and Messrs. Hughes and
Antoun, who are discussed below) were as follows: Mr.&nbsp;Widmar (80%); Mr.&nbsp;Brown (80%); and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson (70%). During the 2012 pay cycle, the committee increased the target bonus percentage of Mr.&nbsp;Widmar to 90% in recognition of
his additional responsibilities in 2012 related to his support of our chief executive officer, as well as for the assumption of the chief accounting officer responsibilities. The target bonus percentages of the other named executive officers
participating in the program did not change. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>- Mid-Year Changes and Related Target Bonus Percentage
Adjustments.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>The Company hired Mr.&nbsp;Hughes as chief commercial officer, effective March&nbsp;19, 2012, with a target bonus percentage of 90%, which was increased to 115% as a result of his appointment on May&nbsp;3,
2012 as chief executive officer. The Company hired Mr.&nbsp;Antoun as chief operating officer, effective July&nbsp;1, 2012, with a target bonus percentage of 75%. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>- Sign-On Bonuses.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>We granted Mr.&nbsp;Hughes and Mr.&nbsp;Antoun a sign-on bonus of $425,000 and $300,000, respectively, less applicable withholdings, to facilitate each
executive&#146;s relocation to Tempe, Arizona and defray expenses related thereto. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Equity-Based Compensation
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We have been a firm proponent of equity-based compensation and have had a historical practice of broad based granting
programs. With the transition of our Company from hi-tech growth to a sustainable provider of solar modules and systems, we have continued to adjust our historical broad based granting practices to those that are more consistent with our business
model. In addition, we have utilized our equity program to support significant retention objectives in light of the substantial transitions faced by the company during 2012. Notably, (i)&nbsp;we adopted the KSTEPP program in order to continuously
incentivize performance over an exceptionally long performance period and (ii)&nbsp;granted time-based restricted stock units with varying vesting schedules to address both short-term and long-term retention concerns, while tying realizable
compensation to the returns of our stockholders. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2012, as part of our continued execution of the Long Term Strategic Plan
and our focus on growth, profitability and liquidity, we determined that equity awards to our named executive officers would consist of grants of restricted stock units with both time-based vesting criteria and KSTEPP performance-based vesting
criteria. The compensation committee believes that this decision furthers the Company&#146;s goal of aligning executive and stockholder interests and relieving anxiety and mitigating any distractions that our executives may feel as part of the
Company&#146;s redirection and the turmoil in the solar industry at this time. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our practice is to grant our equity awards
relatively early in the year. We do not time our grants specifically to avoid any internal &#147;blackouts&#148; or other periods during which our executives and directors may be prohibited by our
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">27 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
Insider Trading Policy or applicable law from trading in our securities, or otherwise to provide any preferential benefit to our executives and directors. Equity grants to our named executive
officers are described in greater detail in the &#147;Grants of Plan Based Awards&#148; table and the &#147;Outstanding Equity Awards at Fiscal Year-End&#148; table. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Long-Term Incentive Program.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>Awards under the long-term incentive programs (i)&nbsp;represent the largest component of executives&#146; compensation, (see &#147;Components of
2012 Executive Compensation&#148;), (ii)&nbsp;serve as a retention tool and (iii)&nbsp;ensure that our executives&#146; compensation is linked to the long-term interests of our stockholders and our Company performance, consistent with our
compensation philosophy. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Although the allocation of long-term incentive program awards may vary between restricted stock units
with time-based vesting criteria and KSTEPP units, the aggregate annual equity award is targeted at the 50th percentile of our peer group (with some flexibility to increase that target based on extraordinary contributions by the executive, as
discussed above). For 2012, the compensation committee determined the applicable percentile for each of the named executive officers as discussed in &#147;Total Compensation Review,&#148; reviewed the value of the annual equity awards granted to
officers in similar positions at peer companies, and then determined to grant approximately half of that value in the form of time-vesting restricted stock units as part of the Company&#146;s annual equity grant. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As described below, the KSTEPP awards were granted to each of the named executive officers based on their position with the Company. As
shown in the Summary Compensation Table, this large grant of the KSTEPP awards results in an appearance of a disproportionate equity grant in 2012, especially relative to the annual equity grants for executives at our peer companies. However, unlike
a typical performance-based equity compensation program in which awards are usually made each year, it is expected that our named executive officers will not receive additional performance-based awards until KSTEPP awards vest or are forfeited
during the performance period (between April&nbsp;1, 2012 and December&nbsp;31, 2020), which is not expected to occur for several years from the grant date. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The KSTEPP awards have an unusually long minimum vesting and overall term. Attainment of the full-vesting goals is estimated to take several years and the earliest any KSTEPP awards can vest, other than
in the event of a Change in Control, is December&nbsp;31, 2014. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Going forward, the compensation committee intends that annual
equity grants of time-vested restricted stock units granted while the KSTEPP awards are outstanding will be in an amount that, when added to the implied annualized value of the KSTEPP awards granted in 2012, will equal the appropriate value for the
peer group percentile applicable to each named executive officer. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Annual Equity Grant.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>We have a
practice of granting named executive officers annual equity compensation grants in the form of restricted stock units. For 2012, the compensation committee granted our named executive officers restricted stock units with time-based vesting criteria.
The awards vest 25% annually, beginning on the first anniversary of the grant date. These time-vesting awards are intended to provide some certainty to our named executive officers of compensation if they remain employed and focused on our Long Term
Strategic Plan, as a complement to the performance-based character of the KSTEPP awards. The compensation committee exercises some discretion, consistent with our compensation philosophy, to tailor these grants to the individual executives in light
of each executive&#146;s performance and contribution to the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The grant value for our named executive officers (other
than Messrs. Ahearn, Antoun and Hughes) was: Mr.&nbsp;Widmar ($1,257,015); Mr.&nbsp;Brown ($494,010); and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson ($878,001). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>KSTEPP.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>During May 2012, the compensation committee approved and adopted the KSTEPP, a performance unit program under the 2010 Omnibus Plan. This program is intended to link
the compensation of the Company&#146;s senior executives with the success of our Long Term Strategic Plan by rewarding achievement of performance objectives that are critical to our Long Term Strategic Plan. The goals of our Long Term Strategic Plan
are to increase the Company&#146;s growth, profitability and liquidity, which results in greater return to our stockholders. The KSTEPP metrics, derived from our Long Term Strategic Plan, align the interests of our executives with those of our
stockholders, consistent with our compensation philosophy. The Company granted awards under the KSTEPP to the named executive officers (other than Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The program is implemented through the grant of performance units. Following the compensation committee&#146;s consideration of peer group data regarding annual equity values, the number of units granted
to each named </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">28 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
executive officer was set based on a tiered approach tied to the role of the applicable executive: chief executive officer (500,000); chief financial officer and chief operating officer
(265,000); and executive vice president of global business development and general counsel and corporate secretary (135,000). </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">A named executive officer will receive one share of Company common stock for each performance unit that vests. Vesting may occur in one of
two ways. First, the KSTEPP awards may vest in full, reduced by any previously vested portion, upon the Company&#146;s achievement in any 12-month period beginning and ending on a calendar quarter (which we refer to as &#147;rolling annual
period&#148;) that occurs between April&nbsp;1, 2012 and March&nbsp;31, 2020 (which we refer to as the &#147;performance period&#148;) of at least 2.8 gigawatts DC of modules sold in sustainable markets and 15% cash adjusted return on invested
capital</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">2</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"> (which we refer to as the &#147;full vesting
condition&#148;). Second, one-third of the KSTEPP award can vest sooner, upon the Company&#146;s achievement in any rolling annual period during the performance period of at least 1.35 gigawatts DC of modules sold in sustainable markets and 13% cash
adjusted return on invested capital (which we refer to as the &#147;partial vesting condition&#148;). The KSTEPP award, or a portion thereof, can vest on the last day of a rolling annual period ending no earlier than December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, no KSTEPP award, nor a portion of such award, can vest unless and until the compensation committee certifies that
the Company has achieved in any rolling annual period during the performance period at least $400 million in KSTEPP adjusted operating income</FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP
STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">3</SUP></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">. The compensation committee believes that the use of rigorous performance objectives over the relatively long
performance period encourages sustained focus on our long-term strategy; however, the provisions allowing for partial vesting provide our executives with some benefit for achievement over this extended period, and mitigate anxiety over potential
payouts that could otherwise distract from focus on our Long Term Strategic Plan. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">KSTEPP awards will not vest unless the named
executive officer is continuously employed by the Company or an affiliate through the applicable vesting date, except, consistent with our other long-term incentive awards, if the named executive officer is eligible for a pro-rata settlement as
described below. Additionally, KSTEPP awards are forfeited upon termination of employment, unless employment is terminated due to death, disability, retirement or termination without cause, and thereafter either the partial and/or full vesting
condition is achieved, in which case the named executive officers are eligible for a full settlement of their vested awards, if any, and a pro-rata settlement of their non-vested awards. The pro-rata settlement will be based on the length of the
named executive officer&#146;s tenure with the Company during the performance period. Additionally, KSTEPP awards will expire and be forfeited with respect to the unvested portion thereof if the vesting condition(s) are not satisfied and the Company
has not achieved in any rolling annual period during the performance period at least $400 million in KSTEPP adjusted operating income, in each case, as of the last day of the performance period (December 31, 2020). </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Notwithstanding the foregoing, in the event of a &#147;change of control&#148; (as defined in the 2010 Omnibus Plan) that occurs during
the performance period, regardless of whether the Company has achieved in any rolling annual period during the performance period at least $400 million in KSTEPP adjusted operating income, 25% of the then-unvested portion of the award will
accelerate and become vested, in order to allow our executives to share in the gains that would, at such time, be realized by our stockholders. The 25% vesting provision supersedes the change of control provisions in the CIC Agreements between the
Company and the named executive officers, which would otherwise provide for full acceleration of the award in the event of a change of control. See &#147;Change in Control Severance Agreements.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, the compensation committee has discretion to further accelerate the vesting of the award in connection with a change of
control, including to amend the award to increase the vested percentage payable upon the occurrence of a change of control, which discretion is expected to be exercised based on the Company&#146;s actual performance tracking relative to the vesting
conditions, providing some flexibility to reward our named executive </FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000;width:13%">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;cash adjusted return on invested capital&#148; for the Company is calculated as follows (i) &#147;KSTEPP adjusted operating income&#148; as defined below minus
income tax expense for such &#147;KSTEPP adjusted operating income&#148; plus depreciation and amortization expense divided by (ii) stockholder&#146;s equity plus debt plus accumulated depreciation minus cash and cash equivalents minus marketable
securities. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"></FONT><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="1"><SUP STYLE="vertical-align:baseline; position:relative; bottom:.8ex">3</SUP>&nbsp;</FONT><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;KSTEPP adjusted operating income&#148; means the Company&#146;s operating income (as defined by GAAP) for a rolling annual period during the KSTEPP performance
period with adjustments for (i)&nbsp;extraordinary, unusual and nonrecurring items including restructuring expenses and (ii)&nbsp;KSTEPP related stock based compensation expense. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">29 </FONT></P>
