 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
officers at a level that is consistent with our stockholders if the Company is performing well in advance of any such change. On at least an annual basis (and at any time when a change of control
is anticipated), the compensation committee will review the Company&#146;s progress towards achievement of either the partial or the full vesting condition and evaluate whether it is appropriate to amend the award (or, if a change of control is
expected, to exercise its discretion) to provide accelerated vesting of a higher portion of the award, effective in all cases only upon an actual change of control. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The number of KSTEPP units granted to our named executive officers (other than Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn) was: Mr.&nbsp;Hughes (500,000); Mr.&nbsp;Widmar (265,000); Mr.&nbsp;Antoun (265,000); Mr.&nbsp;Brown
(135,000); and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson (135,000). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Sign-On Grants.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>Upon their appointment as chief
commercial officer and chief operating officer, the Company granted Mr.&nbsp;Hughes and Mr.&nbsp;Antoun restricted stock units having an aggregate fair market value on the date of grant equal to $1,200,012 and $1,000,015, respectively, which, in
each case, will vest commencing on the first anniversary of the grant date at an annual rate of 25%&nbsp;per year. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Retention Awards.</I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition to the equity awards described above, our named executive officers (other than
Messrs. Ahearn, Hughes and Antoun) received a one-time, special grant of restricted stock units (with award levels based on a multiple of base salary of each of the executives as of January 2012), vesting 40% on the anniversary of the date of grant,
and ratably with respect to the remaining units over the following three years, for the purpose of ongoing retention and focus on the implementation of our Long Term Strategic Plan. The compensation committee believes these awards are appropriate
and reasonable to mitigate any distraction that our executives may feel as part of the Company&#146;s redirection, particularly in light of the volatility of the solar sector and the Company in 2011 and 2012. The form of award and vesting schedule
were designed, consistent with our compensation philosophy, to align the interests of our executives with those of our stockholders, by tying the value of the award to our share price. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The grant date value for our named executive officers (other than Messrs. Ahearn, Hughes and Antoun) was: Mr.&nbsp;Widmar ($1,080,003);
Mr.&nbsp;Brown ($563,003); and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson ($600,009). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Other Executive Compensation Information </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Broad-based Benefits Programs and Other Compensation </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our named executive officers are entitled to participate in the various benefits programs we offer to all of our associates, including a
401(k) plan, medical plan, dental plan, life insurance plan and long-term and short-term disability plans. Under our 401(k) plan, we make a matching contribution equal to 100% of our associates&#146; contributions to the plan up to a maximum of 4%
of an associate&#146;s plan compensation. In 2012, each of Messrs. Hughes, Widmar, Brown and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson received the maximum matching contribution of $10,000. Mr.&nbsp;Antoun received a matching contribution of $7,615, as a result of his
participation in the plan for only a portion of 2012. Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn did not participate in the 401(k) plan. Our named executive officers each have vacation entitlements of four weeks per year. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Employment Agreements and Related Arrangements </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We have entered into employment, confidentiality, non-competition and non-solicitation agreements, and D&amp;O indemnification agreements with each of our named executive officers (except, with respect to
a non-competition and non-solicitation agreement, for Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn). The compensation committee believes these contracts are fair, reasonable, appropriate and necessary to attract and retain the executives who are party to these agreements.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">With the exception of Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn&#146;s agreement (which expressly provided for no severance benefits at the conclusion
of his tenure as interim chief executive officer), the employment agreements generally provide that if the executive&#146;s employment is terminated without &#147;cause&#148; (as defined therein) (or, in the case of Messrs. Hughes and Antoun, if
they resign for &#147;good reason&#148; (as defined therein)), then the executive shall be eligible for (i)&nbsp;salary continuation for a severance period subject to the execution of a release of claims in favor of the Company and subject to a
reduction based on earnings during the severance period, (ii)&nbsp;health benefit coverage for the severance </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">30 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
period, subject to certain contingencies and (iii)&nbsp;an additional 12&nbsp;months&#146; service credit for purposes of determining vesting of equity-based compensation awards (this service
credit will not have an effect on KSTEPP awards). The employment agreements (other than Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn&#146;s) also provide for an additional 12 months service credit for purposes of determining vesting of equity-based compensation in the event
employment terminates due to the executives&#146; death or disability (as defined therein). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Severance benefits, by their
nature, require compensation payments without the receipt of corresponding services. We believe that our employment agreements set a proper balance between providing sufficient protection on employment termination and ensuring the executive has
sufficient personal investment with respect to his or her employment with the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The confidentiality agreements describe
the Company&#146;s expectations of the executives regarding the Company&#146;s proprietary and confidential information. The non-competition and non-solicitation agreements establish a &#147;protected period&#148; that generally matches the
severance period. During the protected period, the senior executives are subject to restrictive covenants as described in the agreement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For more details on these employment agreements and the compensation and benefits payable or to be provided in the event of a termination of employment, see &#147;Executive Compensation &#151; Employment
Agreements and Arrangements&#148; and &#147;Executive Compensation &#151; Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control&nbsp;&#151; Potential Payments Upon Termination of Employment (Other Than in the Context of a Change in
Control).&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Change in Control Severance Agreements </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We have entered into change in control severance agreements (&#147;CIC Agreements&#148;) with each of our named executive officers (other
than Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn). These agreements are intended to align the interests of the executives with our stockholders in a potential change in control situation by mitigating the uncertainty and questions a potential change in control may raise among
such executives, allowing them to focus their continued attention and dedication to their assigned duties. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Equity
Vesting.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>The CIC Agreements provide for full vesting of unvested equity-based compensation upon a change in control of the Company thereby ensuring that such executives are fairly compensated for the lost opportunity to
realize the value of awards that is typically precipitated by a change in control, which is particularly salient for our named executive officers who receive a substantial portion of their income in equity-based compensation that vests over time
(see &#147;Components of 2012 Executive Compensation&#148;). While our equity plans also contemplate vesting of this equity if it is not assumed by a successor entity (see &#147;Executive Compensation &#151; Potential Payments Upon Termination or
Change in Control &#151; Potential Payments Upon a Change in Control &#151; 2010 Omnibus Incentive Compensation Plan&#148;), the CIC Agreements ensure this vesting will occur whether or not the equity-based awards are assumed for executives with
these arrangements; however, the provisions of the award agreement for KSTEPP awards supersede the change of control provisions in the CIC Agreements. See &#147;Equity-Based Compensation &#151; KSTEPP&#148;. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Severance Benefits.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>The CIC Agreements provide a double-trigger severance package for all of our named
executive officers (except for Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn who does not have a CIC agreement) in the event their employment is terminated without &#147;cause&#148; or they resign for &#147;good reason&#148; within two years following a change in control. A
resignation for &#147;good reason&#148; includes any material reduction in the authority, duties or responsibilities held by the executive immediately prior to the CIC date, any material reduction in the annual base salary or annual incentive
opportunity of the executive as in effect immediately prior to the CIC date, or any change of the executive&#146;s principal place of employment to a location more than fifty miles from the executive&#146;s principal place of employment immediately
prior to the CIC date. We believe this standard benefit reinforces the notion that in a change in control situation, all of the executives are similarly situated and must remain focused. The standard benefit is two times their base salary; two times
a bonus amount (which is defined as the greater of (i)&nbsp;the executive&#146;s target annual bonus for the year of termination and (ii)&nbsp;the average of the annual cash bonuses payable to the executive in respect of the three full calendar
years immediately preceding the calendar year that includes the termination date or, if the executive has not been employed for three full calendar years preceding the calendar year </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">31 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
that includes the termination date, the average of the annual cash bonuses payable to the executive for the number of full calendar years prior to the termination date that he or she has been
employed); a pro-rated target bonus; 18 months&#146; health benefit continuation, and outplacement benefits (maximum of $20,000). Severance benefits are subject to the executive&#146;s execution of a release in favor of the Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Parachute Tax Gross-Up.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>In 2011, the Company determined to no longer provide a parachute tax gross-up in new
CIC Agreements entered into thereafter; however, CIC Agreements entered into prior to 2011 provide a parachute tax gross-up (unless the total payments are within 110% of the 280G parachute tax threshold in which case the parachute payments are
reduced to just below the threshold). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Evaluation by the Compensation Committee:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>When the Company
enters into CIC Agreements, the compensation committee reviews the terms of the CIC Agreements in consultation with its independent compensation consultant, assesses the impact of possible payouts under the CIC Agreements in the event of a change in
control and confirms that the CIC Agreements are fair and reasonable to both the executive and the Company. The change in control payment estimates are presented to, and reviewed by, the compensation committee each time compensation is evaluated.
Based on its most recent annual review of the CIC Agreements, the compensation committee continues to believe the payments are fair and reasonable. For a further description of compensation provided in the event of a change in control, see
&#147;Executive Compensation &#151; Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control &#151; Potential Payments Upon a Change in Control.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Tax and Accounting Implications </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Section&nbsp;162(m) of the
Code.</I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With certain material exceptions, Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code (the &#147;Code&#148;) limits the deductibility of compensation paid by a public company in any year to $1&nbsp;million to each of
the chief executive officer and the next three most highly paid executive officers other than the chief financial officer. A transition rule generally applies to compensation paid under plans and arrangements in existence on the date of an initial
public offering, pursuant to which such compensation will not be subject to the $1&nbsp;million limit. Prior to the June&nbsp;1, 2010 annual meeting of stockholders, the Company generally sought to avail itself of this transition rule, and expects
that transition rule to continue to apply to amounts paid or awards granted prior to the date of the Company&#146;s annual meeting held on June&nbsp;1, 2010. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The 2010 Omnibus Plan is designed to enable most executive compensation to be deductible by the Company under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code; however, the compensation committee has not adopted a policy
that all compensation must be deductible, particularly where additional compensation may be needed to attract or retain executives for key leadership positions in the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Section&nbsp;280G of the Code.</I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Section&nbsp;280G of the Code denies a tax deduction on certain compensation payments to any &#147;disqualified individual&#148; (which term
includes our named executive officers) that are contingent upon a &#147;change in ownership or control&#148; of the Company. A tax deduction for compensation in excess of the disqualified individual&#146;s average taxable compensation is denied, but
only if the total change in control payments equal or exceed three times the individual&#146;s average taxable compensation (i.e., the 280G limit). In addition, if the 280G limit is exceeded, a 20% excise tax is imposed on the &#147;disqualified
individual&#148; under Section&nbsp;4999 of the Code. The Company has entered into CIC Agreements with each of the named executive officers (other than Mr. Ahearn). Certain CIC Agreements provide for the Company to gross-up such executive officer
for the 20% excise tax if the applicable compensation exceeds 110% of the 280G limit (payments will be cut back to less than the 280G limit if the 110% threshold is not exceeded). In 2011, the Company determined to no longer provide a parachute tax
gross-up in new CIC Agreements entered into thereafter. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company has estimated the 280G payments that would have been
payable had a change in control occurred and each named executive officer&#146;s employment been terminated on December&nbsp;31, 2012. Mr.&nbsp;Brown and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson are the only named executive officers with such gross-up provisions in
their CIC Agreements at present, and we estimate that as of that date, both would have payments subject to the tax gross-up and deduction disallowance. See &#147;Executive Compensation &#151; Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control
&#151; Potential Payments Upon a Change in Control.&#148; </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">32 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Accounting for Equity-Based Compensation.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>The Company uses ASC
Topic 718 for purposes of determining the fair value of its equity-based compensation. The assumptions used in the calculations of these amounts are included in Note 19, &#147;Share-Based Compensation,&#148; to the Company&#146;s audited financial
statements for the fiscal ended December&nbsp;31, 2012, included in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K filed with the Commission on February&nbsp;27, 2013. The fair value of awards made to each named executive officer in 2012 are set
forth under &#147;Summary Compensation Table.&#148; </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">33 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc480244_8"></A>COMPENSATION COMMITTEE REPORT </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>The following report of the compensation committee is not &#147;soliciting material,&#148; is not deemed &#147;filed&#148; with the
Commission and is not to be incorporated by reference into any other of the Company&#146;s filings under the Securities Act or the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#147;Exchange Act&#148;), except to the extent we specifically
incorporate this report by reference therein. </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Since the formation of the compensation committee in October 2006, Michael
Sweeney has served as chair of the compensation committee. Paul H. Stebbins has served on the compensation committee since his appointment to the board of directors on December&nbsp;19, 2006. William&nbsp;J. Post has served on the compensation
committee since July&nbsp;26, 2010. Richard D. Chapman has served on the compensation committee since July&nbsp;31, 2012. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The
compensation committee is comprised solely of non-associate directors who are each: (i)&nbsp;independent as defined under the NASDAQ listing standards, (ii)&nbsp;a non-associate director for purposes of Rule&nbsp;16b-3 of the Exchange Act, and
(iii)&nbsp;an outside director for purposes of Section&nbsp;162(m) of the Code. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">With a keen sense of awareness of its
fiduciary obligations, the compensation committee actively engages management and reviews data on (i)&nbsp;the relationship between the Company&#146;s incentive compensation programs and the Company&#146;s long-term strategic goals, (ii)&nbsp;the
impact of any individual compensation changes on total compensation (including reviewing executive tally sheets), and (iii)&nbsp;the possibility that any particular program or arrangement could incentivize inappropriate risk-taking behaviors. The
compensation committee believes that the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy is appropriate and that the Company&#146;s incentive compensation programs are important tools that allow all associates, including management, to successfully focus on
matters critical to the Company&#146;s long-term success. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The compensation committee has reviewed and discussed the
&#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; required by Item&nbsp;402(b) of Regulation&nbsp;S-K with management. Based on such review and discussions, the compensation committee recommended to the board of directors that the &#147;Compensation
Discussion and Analysis&#148; be included in this Proxy Statement on Schedule&nbsp;14A and incorporated by reference in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2012. </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc480244_9"></A>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Summary Compensation Table </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table sets forth information with respect to compensation earned for the fiscal years ended December&nbsp;31, 2012,
December&nbsp;31, 2011, and December&nbsp;31, 2010, respectively by each of our chief executive officer, our chief financial officer, and our three other most highly compensated executive officers, as well as our former interim chief executive
officer, with respect to the time he served in the role during the fiscal years ended December&nbsp;31, 2012 and December&nbsp;31, 2011 (collectively, our &#147;named executive officers&#148;). During 2012, the compensation committee approved and
adopted the KSTEPP, a performance award program under the 2010 Omnibus Plan. The KSTEPP performance thresholds, derived from our Long Term Strategic Plan targets and goals, align the interests of our named executive officers with those of our
stockholders, consistent with our compensation philosophy. In May 2012, the Company made performance unit grant awards under the KSTEPP to the named executive officers (other than Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn). In the table below, these KSTEPP awards represent
stock awards of the value shown in the Total column. See the table in footnote 2 below, which shows the separation of performance-based and time-based stock awards granted in 2012. </FONT></P>

a threshold performance goal and pre-established performance criteria within a defined performance period. For a description of this award see &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#151; Components of 2012 Executive Compensation&#148; and
&#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#151; 2012 Compensation Decisions (By Component)&nbsp;&#151; Equity-Based Compensation&nbsp;&#151; Key Senior Talent Equity Performance Program (&#147;KSTEPP&#148;).&#148; </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

of determining vesting of equity-based compensation awards (which equity, other than options granted as part of the Initial Equity Award, will, in the case of restricted stock units, be payable on the vesting date). The additional vesting described
in&nbsp;(iii) above also applies if Mr.&nbsp;Antoun&#146;s employment terminates due to his death or disability. In the event of termination of Mr.&nbsp;Antoun&#146;s employment for any reason, he is entitled to payment of his earned and unused (and
unforfeited) vacation. The severance benefits described in clause (i)&nbsp;above are conditioned upon Mr.&nbsp;Antoun timely delivering a valid and irrevocable release of claims in favor of the Company. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">42 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Antoun is also subject to a separate confidentiality and intellectual property
agreement and a separate non-competition and non-solicitation agreement, the latter of which provides that Mr.&nbsp;Antoun will not compete with the Company or solicit Company associates during a one year restricted period. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Antoun has also entered into a separate CIC Agreement with the Company, the terms of which are described in &#147;Potential
Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control &#151; Potential Payments upon a Change in Control &#151; Change in Control Severance Agreements.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>James G. Brown </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Effective as of December&nbsp;1, 2008, we entered
into an amended and restated employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;James G. Brown, which was further amended effective September&nbsp;1, 2011 to reflect his promotion to president, utility systems business group (from his former title of senior vice
president, project finance). When we announced our long-term strategic plan in 2011, we also announced that Mr.&nbsp;Brown&#146;s role changed to president, global business development. Mr.&nbsp;Brown is currently serving as executive vice
president, global business development. Nonetheless, the terms of his amended employment agreement remain effective. Under the terms of his employment agreement, during 2012 Mr.&nbsp;Brown was entitled to an annual base salary as described under
&#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; 2012 Compensation Decisions &#151; Base Salary,&#148; the opportunity to participate in the Company&#146;s annual bonus program with a target annual bonus of 80%, as described under
&#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; 2012 Compensation Decisions &#151; Cash Incentive Compensation,&#148; other senior level incentive programs, standard employee benefits and four weeks of vacation. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Brown provides that, in the event Mr.&nbsp;Brown&#146;s employment is terminated by us without
cause, Mr.&nbsp;Brown is eligible to receive the following: (i)&nbsp;severance equal to one year of his annual base salary, payable over the 12&nbsp;months following termination, reduced by any earnings of Mr.&nbsp;Brown during the severance period,
(ii)&nbsp;continued medical benefits until the earlier of one year following termination and his coverage under the medical benefit plan of another employer and (iii)&nbsp;an additional one year of service credit for purposes of determining vesting
of equity-based compensation awards (which equity will, in the case of restricted stock units, be payable on the date of termination). The additional vesting described in&nbsp;(iii) above also applies if Mr.&nbsp;Brown&#146;s employment terminates
due to his death or disability. In the event of termination of Mr.&nbsp;Brown&#146;s employment for any reason, he is entitled to payment of his earned and unused (and unforfeited) vacation. The severance and accelerated vesting benefits described
in clauses (i)&nbsp;and, in the case of a termination without cause, (iii)&nbsp;above are conditioned upon Mr.&nbsp;Brown timely delivering a valid and irrevocable release of claims in favor of the Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Brown is also subject to a separate confidentiality and intellectual property agreement and a separate non-competition and
non-solicitation agreement, the latter of which provides that Mr.&nbsp;Brown will not compete with the Company or solicit Company associates during a one year restricted period. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with his initial employment with us, Mr.&nbsp;Brown entered into a separate CIC Agreement with the Company, the terms of
which are described in &#147;Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control &#151; Potential Payments upon a Change in Control &#151; Change in Control Severance Agreements.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Mary Beth Gustafsson </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On February&nbsp;20, 2009, we entered into an employment agreement with Ms.&nbsp;Mary Beth Gustafsson in connection with her service as our vice president and general counsel. This employment agreement
was amended in July 2009 to provide for the accelerated vesting in full of her new-hire equity in the event her employment terminated without cause and amended again in November 2009 to reflect Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson&#146;s promotion to executive vice
president and her assumption of the corporate secretary function at that time. Under the terms of her employment agreement, during 2012, Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson was entitled to an annual base salary as described under &#147;Compensation Discussion and
Analysis &#151; 2012 Compensation Decisions &#151; Base Salary,&#148; the opportunity to participate in the Company&#146;s annual bonus program with a target annual bonus of 60% (which was subsequently increased to 70%), as described under
&#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; 2012 Compensation Decisions&nbsp;&#151; Cash Incentive Compensation,&#148; other senior level incentive programs, standard employee benefits and four weeks of vacation. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">43 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our employment agreement with Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson provides that in the event
Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson&#146;s employment is terminated by us without cause, Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson is eligible to receive the following: (i)&nbsp;severance equal to one year of her annual base salary, payable over the 12 months following termination of
employment, reduced by any earnings of Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson during the severance period, (ii)&nbsp;continued medical benefits until the earlier of one year following termination and her coverage under the medical benefit plan of another employer and
(iii)&nbsp;an additional one year of service credit for purposes of determining vesting on her equity-based compensation awards (other than her sign-on award, which vested in full in 2012) (which equity will, in the case of restricted stock units,
be payable on the vesting date). The additional vesting described in&nbsp;(iii) above also applies if Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson&#146;s employment terminates due to her death or disability. In the event of termination of Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson&#146;s
employment for any reason, she is entitled to payment of her earned and unused (and unforfeited) vacation. The severance and accelerated vesting benefits described in clauses (i)&nbsp;and, in the case of a termination without cause, (iii)&nbsp;above
are conditioned upon Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson timely delivering a valid and irrevocable release of claims in favor of the Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson is also subject to a separate confidentiality and intellectual property agreement and a separate non-competition and
non-solicitation agreement, the latter of which provides that Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson will not compete with the Company or solicit Company associates during a one year restricted period. </FONT></P>

Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control &#151; Potential Payments Upon a Change in Control &#151; Change in Control Severance Agreements.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Potential
Payments Upon Termination of Employment (Other Than in the Context of a Change in Control) </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The table below reflects
the estimated amount of compensation payable to each of the named executive officers (other than Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn) in the event of termination of such executive&#146;s employment as of December&nbsp;31, 2012. The table does not include
Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn, as he was not eligible for any severance benefits under his employment agreement and was not an associate as of such date. The amount of compensation payable to each named executive officer upon involuntary termination without cause
(or, for Messrs. Hughes and Antoun, a resignation for &#147;good reason&#148;) and termination due to disability or death of the executive, in each case, other than in connection with a change in control, is shown below. The amounts shown assume
that such termination was effective as of December&nbsp;31, 2012, and thus include amounts earned through such time and are estimates of the amounts that would be paid out to the executives upon their termination. Unless noted below, for purposes of
the calculations below, we have used a share value of $30.86 per share, which was the closing price of our common stock on December&nbsp;31, 2012, the last trading day in 2012. The actual amounts to be paid out can only be determined at the time of
the executive&#146;s separation from the Company. None of the named executive officers are entitled to compensation upon a termination for cause (except for the value of any earned and unused (and unforfeited) vacation). </FONT></P>

requirements, see &#147;Employment Agreements and Arrangements.&#148; The amounts do not include amounts payable pursuant to the Company&#146;s contracts, agreements, plans or arrangements to the extent they do not discriminate in scope, terms or
operation, in favor of executive officers of the Company and that are available generally to all salaried associates, including payment of accrued rights such as payment for accrued and unpaid vacation. </FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Potential Payments Upon a Change in Control </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Consequences of change in control under equity-based compensation plans </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>2010 Omnibus Incentive Compensation Plan (and 2006 Omnibus Incentive Compensation Plan).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I>The 2010 Omnibus
Plan (and its predecessor, the 2006 Omnibus Incentive Compensation Plan (the &#147;2006 Omnibus Plan&#148;)) provide that, unless otherwise provided in an award agreement, or unless provision is made in connection with the change of control (as
defined below) for assumption of, or substitution for, awards previously granted, in the event of a change of control, any equity awards outstanding as of the date the change of control is determined to have occurred will become fully exercisable
and vested, as of immediately prior to the change of control, and cash incentive awards will be paid out as if the change of control date were the last day of the performance period and assuming target level of performance and all other awards will
be deemed exercisable. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The term &#147;change of control&#148; in the 2010 Omnibus Plan (and the 2006 Omnibus Plan) is defined
generally as the occurrence of any of the following events: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">during any period of 24 consecutive months, a change in the composition of a majority of our board of directors that is not supported by a majority of
the incumbent board of directors; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the consummation of a merger, reorganization or consolidation or sale or other disposition of all or substantially all of our assets, subject to
certain exceptions for transactions that would not constitute a change in control; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the approval by our stockholders of a plan of our complete liquidation or dissolution;&nbsp;or </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">an acquisition by any individual, entity or group of beneficial ownership of a percentage of the combined voting power of our then outstanding voting
securities entitled to vote generally in the election of directors that is equal to or greater than the greater of (a)&nbsp;20% and (b)&nbsp;the percentage of the combined voting power of the outstanding voting securities owned by certain specified
stockholders, with exceptions for certain acquisitions. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>KSTEPP </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In the event of a &#147;change of control&#148; that occurs during the performance period for our KSTEPP awards granted under the 2010
Omnibus Plan, 25% of the then-unvested portion of each award will accelerate and become vested without regard to achievement of the performance goal as of such time, in order to allow our executives to share in the gains that would, at such time, be
realized by our stockholders. The 25% vesting provision supersedes the change of control provisions in the CIC Agreements between the Company and the named executive officers (described below), which would otherwise provide for full acceleration of
the award in the event of a change of control. For more detail about our KSTEPP program, see &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; 2012 Compensation Decisions &#151; Long Term Incentive Programs &#151; KSTEPP.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, the compensation committee has discretion to further accelerate the vesting of the KSTEPP awards in connection with a change
of control, including to amend an award to increase the vested percentage payable upon the occurrence of a change of control, which discretion is expected to be exercised based on the Company&#146;s actual performance tracking relative to the
vesting conditions. On at least an annual basis (and at any time when a change of control is anticipated), the compensation committee will review the Company&#146;s progress towards achievement of either the partial or the full vesting condition and
evaluate whether it is appropriate to amend the award (or, if a change of control is expected, to exercise its discretion) to provide accelerated vesting of a higher portion of the award, effective in all cases only upon an actual change of control.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Change in Control Severance Agreements </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company has entered into change in control severance agreements, referred to as the CIC Agreements, with its executive officers and certain senior management, including each of its named executive
officers presently employed by us. Under the CIC Agreements, if a change in control (substantially as defined in the 2010 Omnibus Plan) occurs, the executive would become immediately entitled to accelerated vesting of all equity-based, long-term
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">46 </FONT></P>



<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
incentive and cash incentive compensation awards (other than awards which by their express terms do not accelerate under the CIC Agreements). </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Executives who are party to a CIC Agreement will also be entitled to severance payments and benefits if the executive&#146;s employment
with the Company is terminated in anticipation of a change in control or if, during the two-year period after a change in control, the executive&#146;s employment is terminated without cause or the executive resigns for &#147;good reason&#148;
(which includes material changes in an executive&#146;s duties, responsibilities or reporting relationships, failure to provide equivalent compensation and benefits and being required to relocate 50 or more miles) (such termination, a
&#147;qualifying termination&#148;). If terminated or separated from the Company under those circumstances, the executive would be entitled to the following additional benefits under the CIC Agreement: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">a lump-sum cash severance payment equal to two times the sum of (i)&nbsp;the executive&#146;s annual base salary (without regard to any reduction
giving rise to good reason) and (ii)&nbsp;the greater of &#151; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the executive&#146;s target annual bonus for the year of termination; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD WIDTH="6%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the average of the annual cash bonuses payable to the executive by us in respect of the three full calendar years immediately preceding the calendar
year that includes the termination date or, if the executive has not been employed for three full calendar years preceding the calendar year that includes the termination date, the average of the annual cash bonuses payable to the executive for the
number of full calendar years prior to the termination date that he or she has been employed; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the continuation of, or reimbursement for, welfare and fringe benefits for 18&nbsp;months after termination of employment;&nbsp;and

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">reimbursement for the cost of executive-level outplacement services (subject to a $20,000 limit). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">To obtain severance benefits under a CIC Agreement, an executive must first execute a separation agreement with the Company that includes
a waiver and release of any and all claims against the Company. For terminations other than a qualifying termination following a change in control, the executive is entitled to accrued rights only. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to the foregoing, in accordance with the CIC Agreements entered into prior to 2011, the Company will make tax
&#147;gross-up&#148; payments to Mr.&nbsp;Brown and Ms.&nbsp;Gustafsson to cover any excise taxes that may be imposed under Section&nbsp;280G of the Code in connection with qualifying termination payments (including the acceleration of equity-based,
long-term incentive and cash compensation upon a change in control) unless the value of the payments and benefits in connection with the change in control does not exceed by more than 10% of the maximum amount payable without triggering any such
taxes, in which case the payments and benefits will be reduced to such maximum amount. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The table below shows the amounts that
would be payable to each of the named executive officers who is party to a CIC Agreement in the event of a qualifying termination following a change in control, if a change in control and the qualifying termination had occurred on December&nbsp;31,
2012, using a share value of $30.86 per share, which was the closing price of our common stock on December&nbsp;31, 2012, the last trading day in 2012. The Company did not enter into a CIC Agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Ahearn and he ceased to be an
associate before December&nbsp;31, 2012. Accordingly, he is not represented on the table. </FONT></P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company will pay the executive an amount equal to two times the sum of (a)&nbsp;the executive&#146;s annual base salary (without regard to any reduction give rise
to good reason) and (b)&nbsp;the greater of (i)&nbsp;the annual bonus and (ii)&nbsp;the average annual cash bonuses payable to the executive in respect to the three (3)&nbsp;calendar years immediately preceding the calendar year that includes the
termination date, or if the executive has not been employed for three (3)&nbsp;full calendar years preceding the calendar year that includes the termination date, the average of the annual cash bonuses payable to the executive for the number of full
calendar years prior to the termination date that he/she has been employed. Further, the Company will pay the executive a prorated bonus based on the number of days the executive was employed by the Company in the fiscal year containing the
termination date. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(2)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The vesting of all time-based equity awards is a &#147;single-trigger&#148; benefit; the time-based equity awards vest upon a change in control. The performance grant
would vest at 25% upon a change in control assumed to occur on December&nbsp;31, 2012. We have assumed that under such circumstances, in light of the limited time that has passed between the grant date and the assumed date of the change in control
and because the compensation committee will not yet have met to track the Company&#146;s performance relative to the performance goals, the compensation committee would not apply any discretion to adjust the 25% vesting provision.
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>ELECTION OF DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Upon the recommendation of the nominating and governance committee of the board of directors, the board of directors has nominated for election at the annual meeting the following slate of ten nominees.
Information about these nominees is provided above under the heading &#147;Directors.&#148; Each of the nominees is currently serving as a director of the Company. The persons appointed in the enclosed proxy intend to vote such proxy for the
election of each of the ten nominees named below, unless the stockholder indicates on the proxy that the vote should be withheld from any or all of the nominees. The Company expects each nominee for election as a director at the annual meeting to be
able to accept such nomination. If any nominee is unable to accept the nomination, proxies will be voted in favor of the remainder of those nominated and may be voted for substitute nominees, unless you have withheld authority. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Nominees </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board of

PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP served as our independent registered public accounting firm and also provided certain tax and other audit-related services. See &#147;Principal Accountant Fees and Services.&#148; Representatives of PricewaterhouseCoopers
LLP are expected to attend the annual meeting, where they will be available to respond to appropriate questions and, if they desire, to make a statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
